  "texts": [
    "In the spatial-cueing paradigm (→ Paradigms), an irrelevant stimulus presented before search-display onset is often referred to as a cue.",
    "Such a (spatially) non-informative cue should not be confused with an informative cue, which provides advance information on the upcoming search display.",
    "Note that a non-informative cue in the context of the spatial cueing paradigm is sometimes referred as \"the distractor\".",
    "Terms Target-defining feature, search-guiding feature, preattentive feature, reported feature, task-irrelevant feature, relative/absolute feature, first-order/second order feature, salience, singleton Visual stimuli can be described as a combination of features (also referred to as properties or attributes).",
    "These can range from the relatively simple, like color, to the complex, like whatever feature or combination of features allows people to recognize a stimulus as a \"cat.\""
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}